"script": "The strange truth about breaking a bone is that, for a while, the healed spot becomes stronger than the original. You see, the moment a bone snaps, blood floods the break and clots into a soft scaffold. Then special cells swarm in, first building a bulging lump of cartilage, then slowly replacing it with fresh, hard bone. And this new growth is bigger than what was there before, forming a thick collar around the old fracture. So for months, that spot is actually tougher than the rest of the bone. Eventually your body sands the lump back down, leaving a seam stronger than steel for its weight.",
